passages.text: Coming back to screens after an extended leave this summer with JP markets considerably higher and hovering near AT (kudos to the "massive" trade deal with US announced mid- July). HF managers are navigating well -- Japan focused managers +14.5% vs TPX +18.2% YTD -- though have been de- grossing over the summer months.

This week brings many overseas investors to Tokyo for a variety of sell- side events. We could see investors start to sharpen their pencils on Japan again as conference season tends to beget foreign flows. I've included a list of laggards below if looking for ideas, including Japan Exchange (freshly added to our Conviction List overnight), Nissan, Panasonic, SMC, KEPCO, etc.
Below is a quick rundown of 10 things that caught my attention over the past few weeks. Look forward to catching up. - Dani

1. HF performance and sector focus. Japan focused managers are up 14.5% YTD (vs TPX +18%) per GS PB, with both beta and alpha driving returns, though gross outflows continued in July and August. In terms of sector allocation, hedge funds in Japan are overweight Industrials, Materials, Healthcare vs underweight in Consumer Discretionary, IT, Real Estate. Interestingly within industrials, Asia industrials still the most crowded YTD though have seen some selling in Japan (perhaps some rotation into China?).
Gross allocation to Japan in the GS Prime book ended at 6.5% (96th percentile 5- year), while Net allocation ended at 5.6% (96th percentile 5- year).

JP Over/Under weights vs. MXJP: Industrials (+7.4%), Materials (+2.3%) and Cons Staples (+1.5%) are the most overweight sectors. Cons Disc is by far the most underweight sector (-8.6%), followed by Info Tech (-2.0%).
Source: Goldman Sachs FICC and Equities and Prime Services data as of Aug 28, 2025. Past performance is not indicative of future results.

2. Foreign flows continue to be supportive. Net foreign flows remain healthy but still well below the Jul 2024 peak. Interestingly US funds are stepping up buying which could support NKY > TPX. Per GIR JP Strategist Bruce Kirk: "US cash buying of Y1.3tr over the last 5 months is the fastest pace of US net buying that we have seen since Abenomics. We think this is a very significant development for overall momentum in the Japanese equities market, and one which could favor NKY names over TPX names should it continue. In our experience, Institutional US investors tend to gravitate more towards blue chip global growth winners, and these names tend to have higher weightings in NKY vs TPX. The main exception to this rule would be Japan Mega Banks, where we have seen continued interest from US LO and Macro investors since late 2022."

3. Politics. Before I went on leave, there was a local obsession around the upper house elections on Jul 20th which ultimately ended up having little impact on markets as results came in line with expectations (the ruling coalition missed majority by a few seats). Fast forward to now, the political calendar is coming back in focus as LDP is expected to

announce results of its July' s Upper House election review today, Sep 2 na, which according to local media reports could serve as precursor to procedures for holding an early party presidential election (as soon as end- Sept). Will Ishiba remain PM, especially now that the LDP has lost majority in both the lower and upper house?

The timing overlap with BOJ' s next meeting Sept 18- 19 adds a new dimension to the macro backdrop as benchmark indices sit at multi- decade highs and inflation measures hover above \(+3\%\) . GIR JP Econ maintain their view that January 2026 will be the best timing for the next BOJ rate hike.

The bright spot? Japan & US (finally) announced a trade agreement on July \(23^{\text{rd}}\) . The main points of the agreement: (1) a reduction in the tariff rate on passenger cars and auto parts from \(25\%\) to \(15\%\) ; (2) an increase in the reciprocal tariff rate from \(+10\%\) to \(+15\%\) ; (3) US \(550 bn in investment (or loans) in the US; and (4) an increase in rice imports from the US (with no change in Japan's total rice imports, as the minimum access quota will be maintained).

8. Shipbuilding - GS JP shipbuilders basket (GSCBJSHP) \(+62\%\) YTD, making it the best performing JP thematic on my screen. GS recently published a bullish global report on shipbuilding here. Historically, share prices are mainly driven by orderbook backlog, but also by earnings beats, as orderbooks determine revenue while earnings depend on cost/efficiency, especially considering orderbooks are capacity-constrained now. Hence, GS research team does not think the current orderbooks fairly reflect LT value, and expect earnings outperformance benefiting from high-ASP orderbooks and low steel prices, could drive share prices.

The play in Japan? Namura Shipbuilding (7014 JT). GIR Nori remains Conviction Buy rated given mid to- long term increase in demand for new ships and potential for an improvement in supply/demand in Japan' s shipbuilding industry as well as for increased defense- related demand positive.

Hoya. While focus has been on Al plays such as Softbank \((+67\% \text{ YTD})\) and cable names (Fujikura \(+90\%\) YTD) recently, demand for some Al- related equipment names has also been strong though not broad- based.

Sustained robust demand for Al semiconductors (GPUs/ASICs/HBM) is supporting strong demand for related SPE. However, investment appetite is mixed depending on the type of equipment and the customer. In terms of stock selection, GIR Nakamura prefers back- end names near- term such as Advantest and Disco, while expects front- end names to trade in a range for now.

As for Disco (just added to our Conviction List), while the market still seems to be skeptical about a meaningful step- up in their shipment figures, GIR Nakamura believes the inflection point is close where Disco's shipments will re- accelerate, driven by new growth drivers such as hybrid bonding. The hybrid bonding technology is already beginning to be adopted by Kioxia Holdings for 3D- NAND, and is scheduled to be adopted by TSMC's A16 process through the adoption of BS- PDN technology in 2H26. Disco's shares are currently trading at \(27 - 28x\) P/E on GIR's FY3/27 estimates, below the mid- cycle P/E of low- 30s.
